literary canon for general readers during the 1920s-1940s. Through this work he became one of the architects of twentieth-century American reading culture."}],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"education":[],"career":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Henry Seidel Canby","first_name":"Henry","last_name":"Canby","middle_name":"Seidel","married_names":[],"gender":"male"},"slug":"henry-canby-1878"},"HD5151":{"id":"HD5151","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":11,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker_bool":true},"parents":{"father_id":"I01316","mother_id":"HD5149"},"tags":["author","editor","musician","radio_host","academic","harvard_graduate","choral_director","notable"],"research_tags":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"marriages":[],"number_of_marriages":0,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_blurb":"Choral director, WNYC host, founder of Canby Singers","notable_category":["arts","music"]},"birth":{"year":1912,"city":"New Haven","county":"New Haven County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1998,"month":2,"day":21,"city":"Cornwall","county":"Litchfield County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","age":85},"residence":{},"burial":{},"baptism":{},"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD6102","display_label":"a fellow descendant who composed and taught piano"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"WNYC radio host of recordings program for decades","body":"Edward Tatnall Canby hosted a weekly recordings program on WNYC New York from 1946 to the mid-1970s — first called 'The New Recordings,' later known as 'Recordings, E.T.C.' He was based in the Saturday Review where he had a parallel record-review column. The program made him one of the most widely-heard American classical and electronic music critics of the postwar era. He was an early advocate of electronic music who brought listeners their first hearing of many experimental composers."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Founded the Canby Singers chamber choir 1950s","body":"Canby founded the Canby Singers chamber choir in New York in the early 1950s — specializing in Renaissance and Baroque repertoire (Monteverdi, Byrd, Lassus, Josquin) but also performing twentieth-century works by Brahms, Hindemith, and Elliott Carter. The choir continued under his name and occasional guidance after his 1980s retirement. He had earlier joined ethnomusicologist Alan Lomax on 1930s tours collecting Appalachian folk music — making the first recordings of folk singer Jean Ritchie."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Audio magazine columnist forty-eight years 1948-1996","body":"Canby's Audio magazine column ran for forty-eight years from 1948 to 1996 — one of the longest single-author runs in American magazine criticism. He fused his interest in musical performance with technical audio engineering, engineering all his WNYC programs himself on acetate-based tape long after polyester had become standard. He authored 'The Saturday Review Home Book of Recorded Music and Sound Reproduction' (1952); his Harvard music degree was earned in 1934."}],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002","role":"student","notes":"Harvard 1934 music degree"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"education":[],"career":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Edward Tatnall Canby","first_name":"Edward","last_name":"Canby","middle_name":"Tatnall","married_names":[],"gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upl